<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>New Inquiry: The Future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 11.65pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; text-indent:-14.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Prof. Phil Redmond [FBB0076]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; text-indent:-14.2pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This submission is made in a personal capacity, but informed by having worked in television for over thirty years and engaged professionally with the BBC, ITV and Channel 4 at many levels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">I created Grange Hill for the BBC and Brookside and Hollyoaks for Channel 4, and through that Mersey Television, based in Liverpool, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">grew to become the UK’s largest independent drama production company and a global centre of technical excellence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In latter years, in my public roles as Creative Director of European Capital of Culture 2008 and then Chair of the Independent Advisory Panel to the UK City of Culture, I have witnessed the collaborative and supportive power of the BBC as the UK’s primary public service broadcaster. It’s scale and reach is something that should not be diluted but </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">strengthened, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">cherished but, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">also be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">encouraged to better promote cultural and creative activity across the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It will not take much. Just a small shift from competitive media company to a refocused public service facilitator. In other words, the BBC does not have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">any UK competitors for its public service remit, it does not need </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to do everything itself, but it can facilitate so many others to do </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">so much </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">more.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This paper cannot fully expand that argument within the constraints set, but does try to answer the questions as set by the terms of reference, and in the same point order.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18.95pt 10pt 0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.82pt; orphans:0; padding-left:1.73pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">What should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-17.45pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#3d3d3d; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘</span><span style="color:#3d3d3d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The control of such a potential power over public opinion and the life of the nation ought to remain with the state’     </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 216pt; orphans:0; text-indent:36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#3d3d3d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Sykes Committee 1923</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In pondering that quote, thought should go not to governments bending the will of people, but the sense of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> well-being</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, pride and confidence that came out of the Olympics, The Queen’s Diamond Jubilee, or the refocusing of civic aspiration in Liverpool, Derry-Londonderry and more recently Hull, through a year of culture. Or</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> how entrepreneurship and business became more accessible to young people following Dragon’s Den and The Apprentice. Or</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> how Sky Sports owes an historical debt to Match of the Day. And how </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">important the BBC has been to all these things. Without the BBC, and its scale and reach, none would have succeeded to the level they did.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-17.45pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Although almost 90 years have elapsed, the BBC should retain the core values and broad recommendations of both the 1923 Sykes Committee and the 1925 Crawford Committee. The first established the mechanism of a public broadcaster funded by a Licence Fee. The second set out the structure of a public corporation granted a Royal Charter with no direct political control.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-17.45pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Both were influenced by the principle that broadcasting was </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘too important to be left to a combine of commercial companies’, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a reference to the BBC’s founding as the British Broadcasting Company, an </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">alliance of radio manufacturers, the purpose of which was </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to develop shared content that would drive the combine of radio manufactures</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> sales.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Yet, John Reith, the BBC’s first </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">commercial </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Managing Director and then, post- Crawford Committee, its first Director General embedded th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">principle </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">of public service </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">with the now well-known mantra</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> educate, inform and entertain.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.6pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In a fragmenting digital world it may be tempting to think that the need for a national public service broadcaster is diminishing, but the need is probably as great now as it was in the 1920’s: to provide a cultural organisation of sufficient scale to encourage content for emerging technology. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.85pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Looking toward the future the challenge is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">not to be dazzled by the allure of online and digital social networking, but to maintain that same desire to provide new </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">cultural</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> opportunities </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for a new breed of content providers, whether that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in television, radio, online or social networking. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The consideration now, perhaps, is to consider whether broadcasting, and the BBC in particular, is now </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">‘...too important to be left to a combine of media companies’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. To return to the 1923 Sykes Committee, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">“…the wave bands available in any country must be regarded as a valuable form of public property and the right to use them for any purpose should be given after full and careful consideration.”  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The future role of the BBC must, therefore, not be considered a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n exclusive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> debate </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for media commentators around </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the future of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">broadcasting and broadcasters – but how broadcasting, as a public property – should be better aligned to wider public service opportunities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.1pt; orphans:0; padding-left:2.45pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The debate should also not consider just the BBC without examining the future, role and need for Chanel 4 as the UK’s second public service provider. The debate should also be widened to include </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">training, skills and job retention. While it has been long argued that competition and therefore plurality will come from the plethora of satellite and digital channels, it has not, to date, been provided by indigenous producers of indigenous original programming on the same scale as the BBC, Channel 3, Channels 4 &amp; 5. Of these, only the BBC can be offered a certain scale of funding to support training. This should be seen as part of its continuing remit to encourage future cultural innovation and, therefor</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e innovators.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.35pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.2pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">While part of this debate will revolve around the role of social media, what is often overlooked, but should not be, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is that despite social media’s ability to reach large numbers of people very quickly, they can only do so if user</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s, especially new users, know they exist</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. Despite the allure, digital media requires the same level of marketing and promotion as every other form of publication and promotion. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Social media</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> needs a shop window and that should continue to be one of the BBC’s central roles: the encouragement and promotion of creativity and innovation, but more than this, the development of the t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">alent to enable this to happen.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.35pt; padding-left:3.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">It is therefore probably an opportune moment to re-assess the Rheithian </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">mantra </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">‘educate, inform and entertain’ and redefine what each actually means for the 21</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">st,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> as opposed to the 20</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Century. Put another way, is a term from an analogue age still fit for purpose in a digital universe? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.35pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.2pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Instead then of ‘educate, inform and entertain’ the digital mantra should </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">be to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">‘inform, entertain and connect”.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 40.83pt; orphans:0; padding-left:1.72pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">As well as could have been predicted/expected within the wider public sector culture where, perhaps, performance monitoring and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Value </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">For</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Money (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">VFM</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> targets have skewed service provision.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Broadly, yes – but external pressures have resulted in too high an emphasis on raw numbers – in terms of ratings, media headlines and promotion of celebrity - as against audience reach, inclusion and social impact.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> There is a need for a better methodology to measure the BBC’s ‘social impact’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Such a methodology should also be sued to measure </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the role of the BBC in aligning itself with wider public service agendas as well as becoming much more of a recognized, and celebrated, cultural incubator.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 44.13pt; orphans:0; padding-left:5.52pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The BBC should be asked to do several things:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.64pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.36pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">maintain the high standards it sets across all its mainstream channels and online activity, but in doing so review how it can rationalise its output to find space to:</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.87pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">become the national incubator for cultural innovation and talent development</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.85pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.15pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">continue developing its recent policy of greater partnership and encourage greater access to its regional resources including</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the use of regional volunteers, especially in local radio</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.87pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.13pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">align itself, where appropriate, with other national public service or social agendas such as health, education and arts provision</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> as a greater</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> part of its output</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.59pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">capitalise on Media City in Salford, as the geographical centre of the UK</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The only ‘target’ beyond a core public service remit to ‘inform, entertain and connect’ should be to ‘serve all Licence holders’. By encouraging greater partnerships across the UK; greater use of Salford as a geographical centre; access to its regional resources and providing an open framework for volunteers to make use of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> those</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> resources, most audiences could be reached. However, the emphasis must be on creating an open framework for facilitation rather than any form of top down policy or regulated social inclusion checklist. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leave</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">s entirely to others to create?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">With a more open and regionally inclusive </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">BBC no ‘quotas’ </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">imposed. While it may have been appropriate to help try and stimulate the market for independent production in the past, there is probably now a stronger VFM argument to allow the BBC to make such decisions on an operational need and costs basis.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There is no hard and fast rule on production costs or creative ambition, as it too often depends on the personnel engaged and the technology deployed. In certain genres of production, like long-form drama, such as Eastenders, or studio-based current affairs, like Newsnight, economies of scale should always return better VFM for in-house production, while single drama or documentaries should be more efficiently produced by specialised production companies. On the other hand, smaller specialised </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">companies may not have the resources to develop or research programme ideas over a longer period nor be able to amortise costs across several productions and/or locations. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Beneath this question is the biggest challenge facing not only the BBC, but the UK Broadcasting sector: the curate’s egg (or perhaps dog’s breakfast?) that has underpinned and bedeviled broadcasting policy since the 1949 Beveridge Committee and its Minority Report that recommended an end to the BBC monopoly by proposing commercial television. Since then terrestrial broadcasters, for valid reasons, have had to manage a duopoly in which commercial broadcasters where asked to be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘not too commercial and provide public service progamming’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> while the BBC’s was steadily encouraged to be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘more competitive, but not too commercial’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The system worked reasonably well for around 50 years, but over the last decade, with the increasing expansion of commercial alternatives, it has come under increasing strain.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">If it is an opportune moment to review the BBC’s social and cultural remit, then it is also an opportune moment to finally sever broadcasting’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> cultural Gordian knot. The BBC should continue to be funded by the Licence Fee and continue to redefine its role as the nation’s public service broadcaster. Elsewhere, ITV, Channel 5 and even Channel 4 should be freed from explicit public service remits to become truly commercial in nature including, if necessary or desired, merger.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> They should not be propped up at the expense of weakening the BBC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">This would not result in the BBC becoming ‘boringly public service orientated” – as through </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">role of cultural innovator it should be free to take risks. Risks that led to Monty Python, broadcast Snooker and Grange Hill. The commercial channels need only look to the print media, with The Economist, The FT or Random House and Penguin to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">realis</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">e that commercialism comes in many forms and, in fact, social and economic issues that affect a great number of people can also deliver large audiences, readerships and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">returns. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 44.13pt; orphans:0; padding-left:5.52pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">of such activities beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Not qualified or have access to the data to comment on the first question.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">On the second question: the BBC should be allowed to pursue any and all commercial activities that support, come from and/or </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">promote its role as the public service broadcaster outlined above. All such revenue should be re</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">invested in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">service provision, especially in terms of funding greater partnerships and access across its regions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 44.13pt; orphans:0; padding-left:5.52pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and ne</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">w ways of distributing content?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">While much of what the BBC needs </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">technically </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">is probably available commercially, innovation always requires a move away from the norm when the acquisition of custom-built technology can be both commercially and creatively sensitive, as well as more costly. The BBC should be allowed to continue its traditional role of technological innovation attached to its role as public service provider. If it requires proprietary technology to deliver or expand its services, as with the BBC iPlayer, then it should continue to do so, while looking for potential revenue opportunities through licensing such technology.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 44.13pt; orphans:0; padding-left:5.52pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The Licence Fee, as a widely accepted accepted working model, should be retained, although a greater emphasis on its cultural value, through more regional engagement and cultural innovation, should be encouraged.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Referring</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> to Paragraph 27 and 28 above, consideration should also be given to the revenue generated by Channel 4 as the UK’s second national public service broadcaster and whether it’s original remit </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">‘to cater for audiences not catered for elsewhere’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is still necessary 30 years after its creation. Channel 4 could be merged with the BBC; its content merged with the BBC national channels; its brand retained in place of BBC4 while its advertising revenue could be used to supplement or subsidise the Licence Fee as well as offer a new funding stream to underpin greater social and regional engagement. Plurality of service and choice is a red herring as this could be dealt with by internal monitoring in the same way that the BBC manages children’s programming.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Is there a case for distributing funding for public service conte</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">nt more widely beyond the BBC?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">No. This is an old industry chestnut, usually peddled by other struggling broadcasters or those that would like guaranteed and secure funding for their own </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">specific </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ventures. Apart from considering the need to keep the support of those who pay the Licence Fee, the public, by maintaining that the BBC is a “good thing”, which will be harder if the list of those receiving licence fee funds grows, any ‘top slicing’, no matter how it is presented, would dilute the BBC’s ability to remain the national public service broadcaster. It would, once more, introduce the same confusion </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">between ‘public’ and ‘commercial provision’ as outlined between the BBC and ITV in paragraph 25 above.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The real issue to consider is scale. Without the secure funding provided by the Licence Fee the BBC could not deliver </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the quality nor scale of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">broadcasts around events like the Olympics, Children In Need or its recent support for the UK City of Culture programme. This is what makes the BBC ‘special’ and why, despite the need for a review of its social remit, it needs to be protected, just as the Sykes Committee suggested in 1923, as an invaluable national resource.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries?</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">None. Broadcasting is particular to the country and therefore the culture it operates within. It is often cited that t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he BBC is the envy of the world. I</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, but</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> because of its scale, secure funding and independent charter meaning that it provides an unparralled service of quality and impartiality – for the UK. That is not to be confused with the quality of its programming or evolving governance arrangements. It is the scale and funding that needs to be protected. It is a national success story and despite recent difficulties, echoed elsewhere across the public sector, it should be celebrated as such.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 44.13pt; orphans:0; padding-left:5.52pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> held accountable beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whether labeled Trustees or Governors, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he overriding issue is one of trust and faith in whatever system is in place.  While the publication of minutes, voting records, expenses etc provides </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">level of transparency, in every forum in public life it is recognised that some form of confidentiality is required both to encourage frank debate and protect sensitive information.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> That requires the public to trust and put their faith in those charged with governance.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A policy of centralisation always breeds a feeling, whether warranted or not, of disconnect, especially if a governing body is separated from its core activities by geographical distance. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">t would help </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> future governance body of the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">seen to be more clearly representative of as wide a cross section of the population as possible. This is always challenging in a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">governing </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">body small enough to manage effectively, but large enough to be socially inclusive. The solution would be to devolve the structure and organisation of any future governing body </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to better reflect </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">clearly defined major geographical areas, like the North West, North East, Midlands etc rather than the current </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and simplistic </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Nations structure. At the moment The North West has probably </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">more Licence Fee holders than Scotland and Wales yet has no separate representation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Each region should then have its own local governance board</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, perhaps an expanded role for the current Audience Councils,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> dealing with the service provision in their </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">designated </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">geographical areas. The Chairs of these devolved Boards would then become de facto members of the national governance body, thus providing a far greater level of contribution and feeling of representation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">That national governance body, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">drawing its membership and authority </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">from the regions, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">help avoid the risk of becoming too London-centric. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">In terms of regulation, the BBC should stand apart from Ofcom to provide a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">real </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">plurality</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, that of cultural interpretation around</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the issues of taste and decency. This would also prevent broadcasting in general be</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> captured by one regulatory body’s interpretation of cultural nuances.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.65pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Yes. For the same reasons the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Crawford Committee gave in 1925 – and every major enquiry since.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">6 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 11.65pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>